Extending hypeR

Source: vignettes/docs/extending.Rmd
extending.Rmd

hypeR is an R package focused on the downstream analysis of geneset enrichment workflows. Because there are many upstream tools for performing enrichment, users may opt for those while also planning to use the visualization, summarization, and reporting features offered by hypeR This task is straightforward given the object oriented nature of hypeR

In this example, we will perform enrichment on a differential expression signature using fgsea, a popular R package for Fast Gene Set Enrichment Analysis, and coerce the results into a hyp object, compatible with all hypeR methods.

library(dplyr)
library(magrittr)
library(fgsea)
library(hypeR)

Signature

Start with a differential expression dataframe.

hypdat <- readRDS(file.path(system.file("extdata", package="hypeR"), "hypdat.rds"))

Rank genes by upregulation and extract a weighted signature.

df <- hypdat$limma

df.up <- df %>% filter(t > 0 & fdr < 0.001) %>% arrange(desc(t))

Wrapping fgsea to return a hyp object

To wrap third-party packages, we create modified version of the hypeR() function that calls external packages when performing the enrichment analysis, and then coerces the results into a hyp or multihyp object. We will wrap additional packages based on user demand.

fgsea_to_hyp <- function(signature,
                         genesets, 
                         nperm=10000, 
                         direction=c("up", "dn"),
                         pval=1, 
                         fdr=1,
                         quiet=TRUE,
                         ...) {
    
    # Handling of multiple signatures
    if (is(signature, "list")) {
        
        if (is.null(names(signature))) {
            stop("Lists of signatures must be named")
        }

        lhyp <- mapply(function(x, id) {
            cat(.format_str("{1}\n", id))

            fgsea_to_hyp(x,
                         genesets=genesets, 
                         nperm=nperm, 
                         direction=direction, 
                         pval=pval,
                         fdr=fdr,
                         quiet=quiet)

        }, signature, names(signature), USE.NAMES=TRUE, SIMPLIFY=FALSE)

        # Wrap list of hyp objects in multihyp object
        return(multihyp$new(data=lhyp))
    }

    # Save original arguments
    args <- as.list(environment())

    # Default arguments
    direction <- match.arg(direction)
    args$direction <- direction

    # Handle gsets
    if (is(genesets, "list")) {
        gsets.obj <- gsets$new(genesets, quiet=quiet)
    }
    else if (is(genesets, "gsets") | is(genesets, "rgsets")) {
        gsets.obj <- genesets
    } 
    else {
        stop("Genesets must be gsets/rgsets object or named list of genesets")
    }
    
    # Save gsets object
    args$genesets <- gsets.obj

    # Run fgsea
    results <- fgsea(stats=signature, pathways=gsets.obj$genesets, nperm=nperm, ...)
    
    # Reformat results
    results <- data.frame(results)
    colnames(results) <- c("label", "pval", "fdr", "score", "nes", "nme", "found", "le")
    results$pval <- signif(results$pval, 2)
    results$fdr <- signif(results$fdr, 2)
    results$geneset <- sapply(results$label, function(x) length(gsets.obj$genesets[[x]]))
    results <- dplyr::select(results, c("label", "pval", "fdr", "score", "nes", "nme", "geneset", "found", "le"))
    
    #If hits are found format dataframe
    if (!is.null(results)) {
        data <- results %>%
                dplyr::filter(pval <= args$pval) %>%
                dplyr::filter(fdr <= args$fdr) %>%
                dplyr::arrange(pval)
        
        if (direction == "up") data %>% dplyr::filter(score > 0)
        if (direction == "down") data %>% dplyr::filter(score < 0)
        
        # Empty plots
        plots <- setNames(data$label, data$label) %>%
                 lapply(function(x) ggempty())
    }

    # Wrap dataframe in hyp object
    hyp_obj <- hyp$new(data=data, plots=plots, args=args)
    return(hyp_obj)
}
genesets <- hyperdb_rgsets("KEGG", version="92.0")
hyp_obj <- fgsea_to_hyp(signature, genesets)

The resulting hyp or multihyp objects are compatible with all hypeR functionality.
